---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { atlas } from '../../utils/atlas';
import { runPillarLOO } from '../../utils/pillar-prediction-eval';

const a = atlas();
const eval_ = runPillarLOO();

function pct(num: number, den: number): string {
  if (den === 0) return 'n/a';
  return `${((num / den) * 100).toFixed(1)}%`;
}
function pillarName(id: string): string {
  return a.pillars.get(id)?.pillar.name ?? id;
}
function pillarPath(id: string): string {
  const p = a.pillars.get(id);
  if (!p) return id;
  const doc = a.doctrines.get(p.doctrineId);
  return `${doc?.short_name ?? p.doctrineId} › ${p.pillar.name}`;
}
function doctrineHref(id: string): string {
  return `/doctrine/${a.pillars.get(id)?.doctrineId ?? id}`;
}
const perState = [...eval_.perState.entries()].sort((a, b) => b[1].scored - a[1].scored);
const generatedAt = eval_.generatedAt;
---
<Base title="Pillar prediction — backtest" wide>
  <p class="kicker">Research</p>
  <h1>Pillar prediction — backtest</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Same engine as doctrine prediction, finer-resolution labels.
    Predicts the specific doctrine <em>pillar</em> an event serves
    (MIC2025/next-gen-it; MCF/civil-infrastructure-targeting;
    NCS-2023/disrupt-and-dismantle) rather than just the parent
    doctrine. Candidate space is 129 pillars vs 61 doctrines —
    twice the resolution.
  </p>
  <p class="meta">Generated {generatedAt} · n={eval_.scored} events with pillar-level labels</p>

  <section>
    <h2>Headline</h2>
    <div class="stat-grid">
      <div class="stat"><strong>{pct(eval_.hit1, eval_.scored)}</strong>top-1 hit</div>
      <div class="stat"><strong>{pct(eval_.hit3, eval_.scored)}</strong>top-3 hit</div>
      <div class="stat"><strong>{pct(eval_.hit5, eval_.scored)}</strong>top-5 hit</div>
      <div class="stat"><strong>{(eval_.meanRecall3 * 100).toFixed(1)}%</strong>recall@3</div>
      <div class="stat"><strong>{eval_.mAP.toFixed(3)}</strong>mAP</div>
      <div class="stat"><strong>{pct(eval_.doctrineRightPillarWrong, eval_.scored)}</strong>doctrine-right, pillar-wrong</div>
    </div>
    <p class="reading">
      <strong>The pillar engine performs essentially as well as the
      doctrine engine despite the candidate space being twice as
      large.</strong> top-1 38.5% vs doctrine 39.3% — a single
      percentage point — and pillar predictions carry twice the
      analytic resolution. The "doctrine-right pillar-wrong"
      number ({pct(eval_.doctrineRightPillarWrong, eval_.scored)})
      is striking: when the engine misses, it usually misses on the
      parent doctrine entirely, not just the within-doctrine pillar.
      The two engines aren't really doing different jobs — they're
      operating on the same predictive signal at different
      resolutions.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Per-state — where pillar resolution helps</h2>
    <table class="state-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>state</th><th>n</th><th>pillar top-1</th><th>pillar top-3</th><th>recall@3</th><th>mAP</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {perState.map(([state, row]) => (
          <tr>
            <td><code>{state.toUpperCase()}</code></td>
            <td>{row.scored}</td>
            <td>{pct(row.hit1, row.scored)}</td>
            <td>{pct(row.hit3, row.scored)}</td>
            <td>{(row.meanRecall3 * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            <td>{row.mAP.toFixed(3)}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p class="reading">
      <strong>US 81.0% pillar top-1</strong> — the engine almost
      always picks the right specific NCS-2023 pillar
      (disrupt-and-dismantle vs secure-by-design vs persistent-engagement).
      <strong>KP jumped from 42.2% (doctrine) to 57.1% (pillar)</strong>
      because Byungjin's revenue-aggregation vs nuclear-modernization
      vs sanctions-evasion pillars are operationally distinct —
      finance events go to one pillar, defense-contractor events to
      another, and the engine picks correctly. The pillar level
      <em>matches reality</em> for those programs.
    </p>
    <p class="reading">
      <strong>CN 46.3% (doctrine) → 21.6% (pillar)</strong> is the
      one major regression. CN's pillars overlap heavily:
      MIC2025/semis, MIC2025/aerospace, MCF/dual-use-research, and
      MCF/bulk-pii-humint all share sector signatures (semis, defense,
      aviation, telecom). The engine can't separate them on
      sector+country features alone; this is the same data-richness
      problem the actor attribution engine has for CN MSS clusters
      — and the same fix applies (per-pillar tradecraft / target-org
      features).
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Top confusion pairs</h2>
    <table class="conf-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>predicted pillar</th><th>actual pillar</th><th>×</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {eval_.confusion.slice(0, 12).map((c) => (
          <tr>
            <td><a href={doctrineHref(c.predicted)}>{pillarPath(c.predicted)}</a></td>
            <td><a href={doctrineHref(c.actual)}>{pillarPath(c.actual)}</a></td>
            <td><strong>{c.count}</strong></td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p class="reading">
      The headline confusion <em>kp/8th-congress.../revenue-aggregation
      → kp/byungjin/sanctions-evasion-revenue</em> ×8 is the
      doctrine-succession pattern again (Byungjin was the original
      framework, 8th Congress Defense Plan succeeded it, both have a
      "revenue" pillar pointing at the same DPRK financial-theft
      operations). Operationally these are equivalent; tagging
      against one or the other is editorial preference. Worth folding
      these into a single canonical pillar in v0.2.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What this changes for the product</h2>
    <p>Four engines now operate on the same atlas:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Pillar prediction (NEW)</strong> — same accuracy as
        doctrine, twice the resolution. Analytically the better
        choice for journalists and CISOs: "this serves
        NCS-2023/disrupt-and-dismantle" is more useful than "this
        serves NCS-2023".
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Doctrine prediction</strong> — coarser fallback,
        used to surface the parent doctrine when the pillar engine
        is uncertain.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Actor attribution</strong> — the "who" candidate
        shortlist.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Joint engine</strong> — confidence layer and
        novelty flag.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Concrete v0.1 product output for a live unattributed event:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Pillar engine top-3 (the "why, specifically" — 57.2% hit)</li>
      <li>Doctrine engine top-1 (the "why, broadly" — 39.3% hit)</li>
      <li>Actor engine top-5 (the "who" candidate set — 59.3%)</li>
      <li>Joint pair if co-occurrence ≥ 2 (the confident-pattern claim — US 76.7%)</li>
      <li>Novelty flag if joint top has zero co-occurrence</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Engine source: <code>src/utils/pillar-prediction.ts</code>.
      JSON: <a href="/api/pillar-eval.json">/api/pillar-eval.json</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .meta { color: var(--ctp-subtext0); font-size: 0.9375rem; margin: 0 0 1.5rem; }
  .stat-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(140px, 1fr));
    gap: 0.5rem;
    margin: 1rem 0 1.5rem;
  }
  .stat {
    display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.125rem;
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    background: var(--ctp-mantle);
    border: 1px solid var(--ctp-surface0);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--ctp-subtext1);
  }
  .stat strong { font-size: 1.5rem; color: var(--ctp-text); font-weight: 600; }
  table { border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; font-size: 0.875rem; margin: 0.75rem 0 1rem; }
  th, td { text-align: left; padding: 0.375rem 0.625rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--ctp-surface0); vertical-align: top; }
  th { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.75rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; color: var(--ctp-subtext0); }
  td { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.8125rem; }
  td a { color: var(--ctp-text); }
  td a:hover { color: var(--ctp-blue); }
  .reading {
    background: var(--ctp-mantle);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--ctp-blue);
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    margin: 0.75rem 0;
  }
  ol li, ul li { margin: 0.4rem 0; }
</style>
